00:16:46.119 --> 00:16:48.280
but there's a whole keynote tomorrow, so you should go to that.

00:16:48.280 --> 00:16:49.400
Hans will give a brilliant talk.

00:16:50.599 --> 00:16:53.000
But a rough sort of hand-wavy thing.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:57.080
It's faster for some cases, particularly the repeated joins,

00:16:57.080 --> 00:17:00.599
repeated queries, sorry, so you're doing the same query over and over again.

00:17:00.599 --> 00:17:03.719
For joining data, it's also got some cool inbuilt stuff in DuckDB

00:17:03.719 --> 00:17:07.160
that makes joining a bit quicker than, say, nanoparquet or something like that,

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:07.959
so it's quite nice.

00:17:10.119 --> 00:17:12.839
Summary, there's not a single solution.

00:17:13.640 --> 00:17:17.239
As I've got older, I value stability quite a lot.

00:17:17.239 --> 00:17:20.280
You know, I still enjoy messing about with new stuff,

00:17:20.280 --> 00:17:22.599
but I also like things that just work.

00:17:23.640 --> 00:17:26.199
And I've tried to make this talk of the stuff that I've talked about,

00:17:26.199 --> 00:17:29.560
you know, CSV files, parquet files, DuckDB,

00:17:29.560 --> 00:17:32.040
they're sort of stable tools, they're not going anywhere,

00:17:32.040 --> 00:17:35.319
they solve your problem, and depending on your current problem,

00:17:35.319 --> 00:17:36.439
you should choose one of them.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.079
And if you've got 10 minutes, you can just mess about with them

00:17:39.079 --> 00:17:40.839
and get a rough idea of what works.

00:17:41.719 --> 00:17:44.359
Lots of blog posts in Jumping Rivers, so if you go to our website,

00:17:44.359 --> 00:17:46.680
we've done a few, three or four blog posts in this stuff,

00:17:46.680 --> 00:17:47.959
it's got more details.

00:17:47.959 --> 00:17:50.599
But thank you very much for listening, and happy to take any questions.

00:17:50.599 --> 00:17:58.599
**Amy Henshaw**

00:17:58.599 --> 00:18:00.760
Well, there seems to be an issue with our Slido right now,

00:18:00.760 --> 00:18:02.760
but I do have a question for you about,

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:06.760
you're talking about different file types and how to read those in.

00:18:06.760 --> 00:18:10.119
What are you using to, when you do read that data in Transformer,

00:18:10.119 --> 00:18:12.760
and I know Spark has become more popular with data size,

00:18:12.760 --> 00:18:17.719
like, speed of running those queries and doing data manipulation on those.

00:18:17.719 --> 00:18:19.239
**Jordan Mason**

00:18:19.239 --> 00:18:23.479
So, I think it depends on your use case and what you care about.

00:18:24.119 --> 00:18:29.640
And so, I suppose the main thing I've been thinking about doing this talk is,

00:18:30.920 --> 00:18:35.880
you've got an app, or you've got a Quarto document or a Markdown document,

00:18:35.880 --> 00:18:38.439
and you've got a dataset that you're pulling in, it's quite big,

00:18:38.439 --> 00:18:40.760
maybe it's in a pen and connect, or maybe it's somewhere else,

00:18:41.479 --> 00:18:44.760
and you're trying to optimize that building of the document.

00:18:44.760 --> 00:18:46.520
So, a lot of the clients that we work with,

00:18:46.520 --> 00:18:48.439
they don't need the data in real time.

00:18:48.439 --> 00:18:52.199
You know, things change in the last three hours, but who really cares?

00:18:52.199 --> 00:18:54.520
So, you could do a little run at the stroke of midnight,

00:18:54.520 --> 00:18:56.920
convert to whatever format you want,

00:18:57.719 --> 00:18:59.959
and then that's what you can use for the rest of the day.

00:18:59.959 --> 00:19:02.680
And at the stroke of midnight, you can regenerate that sort of cache file,

00:19:02.680 --> 00:19:05.959
you know, whether it's a parquet file, whether it's something in DuckDB.

00:19:05.959 --> 00:19:09.160
So, it's done sort of not quite in real time, it's done,

00:19:09.160 --> 00:19:10.439
and then you've just got a very nice,

00:19:10.439 --> 00:19:13.000
quick way of generating Quarto shiny apps, that sort of stuff.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:14.199
Yes, definitely.

